english:
  title: Arriving at Gaetae Temple on Cheonho Mountain on the Twenty-Fourth Day of the Third Month
  author: Seok Won-gam
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Three times this year I have passed through Cheonho Mountain.
    Within Cheonho Mountain, white clouds drift and drift.
    The white clouds boast of their leisure in the mountain's heart—
    they surely laugh at the weary traveler passing below.

    I speak to you, white clouds: do not mock me.
    My path knows no right or wrong.
    How do I know that one day I shall not settle
    in these fair hills and valleys,
    and return to share stories with you?
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Seok Won-gam was a Buddhist monk of the Joseon period; the temple mentioned (Gaetae Temple) was located on Cheonho Mountain
  - key: ''
    value: The poem reflects on the speaker's repeated journeys through the same landscape, contrasting the clouds' static contentment with the speaker's wandering state
  - key: ''
    value: The final lines express the Buddhist-influenced philosophy of non-attachment and the possibility of future dwelling in nature
